replies.body:
Aye, this.

@Eedat, As explained by the algebra, there is literally no numerical change in the entire game if you implement this change. You're not "getting rid" of the total AD scaling, you're splitting it, placing the base damage part of tAD directly onto the relevant ability, and keeping the bonus damage part separate. The numbers are identical at the end, all this means is that Riot can then choose to tweak base and scaling independently. :)

If the algebra isn't your strong suit, check the Yorick-relevant link I shared in the post for a hands-on example. It displays how the same damage numbers can be displayed as either x+total% or y+bonus%, and be numerically and functionally identical. This change doesn't shift a single number out of place in all of League of Legends, it just gives Riot an easier time tweaking things on those champs in future, so that those champs you are so concerned about can be buffed or nerfed WITHOUT impacting the kit more than is needful.
